programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. When Jason Bretell and Jennifer Pancari first set eyes on a dilapidated bluestone cottage in the Melbourne bayside suburb of Williamstown, it was love at first sight. The 150-year-old derelict structure was frozen in time, with decaying tools and other remnants among the ruins: bits and pieces Jason and Jen hope to salvage as they bring the place back to life. Their plan is to restore the tiny four-roomed cottage and add a two-storey contemporary townhouse on the back: a modern, edgy, industrial-style structure that contrasts sharply with the heritage bluestone frontage. It sounds romantic, but the reality is far from that. Storm water damage means the whole front wall has to be deconstructed and rebuilt, and there's more grief when the original roof won't match up with its new counterpart. Jason and Jen are hands-on when it comes to selecting materials, they have a wedding planned mid-build, and with no architect and tight finances, Jen takes on designing the kitchen and bathroom, as well as starting a new job. The couple are spreading themselves thin in an effort to see their project through. Can they find the balance between the old and the new to salvage this little piece of history?

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. Milly Bradshaw lived with her two children in the Brisbane valley of Brookfield for six years before she met Andrew Wilson. In time, the place became the base for their blended family and was perfect for their shared dream of running a small farm. They started buying cattle, but with their run-down weatherboard cottage well past its use-by date, it was clear they needed a new dwelling: a modern farmhouse. The brief to their architect was simple: a unique home making the best of its location, and as different as possible from the traditional ranch style. Their architect delivered a design that's telescopic, angular and modern in shape, rising from one storey to three and culminating in a two-storey glazed portal framing the master bedroom. Projecting out of the landscape and clad in natural materials such as spotted gum boards, it's a contemporary take on rural living. Andrew, who has plumbing skills, sets out with right-hand man Hamish, an accomplished carpenter, to bring this dynamic form to life. But Milly is busy working so won't be there for the key decisions. The project's scope is breath-taking and even the architect admits it's no easy build. It's supposed to be the next step in their lives together, but as Andrew gets swamped in a quagmire of decision making, it might have the opposite effect

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. Dean and Sherrill Lamb yearn for a simpler existence for themselves and their three children. They've already sold their fruit shops and are planning to sell their house in the pursuit of total self-sufficiency. Designing a new four-pavilion structure themselves, they plan to minimise their carbon footprint while constructing it at Pipers Creek, north of Melbourne. Interested in natural building options, they've settled on one with excellent environmental properties and perfect credentials for Australian conditions: a house made of straw. Their straw bale walls are to be complemented by rammed earth flooring, with every element utilising natural alternatives wherever possible, recycled windows and doors, and a mini-wind turbine to provide power. To help bring it in on budget, Dean and Sherrill will be doing all this themselves, and Dean plans to run straw bale house building classes too. It could provide the perfect balance, helping them to tread gently on the planet while living a more sustainable existence, but although it's a well-intentioned goal, it may not be realistic. Focus soon turns to merely keeping their dream afloat. When you lack experience, manpower and money, the inevitable response is to compromise. The question is, by how much?(n)

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. When Jason Bretell and Jennifer Pancari first set eyes on a dilapidated bluestone cottage in the Melbourne bayside suburb of Williamstown, it was love at first sight. The 150-year-old derelict structure was frozen in time, with decaying tools and other remnants among the ruins: bits and pieces Jason and Jen hope to salvage as they bring the place back to life. Their plan is to restore the tiny four-roomed cottage and add a two-storey contemporary townhouse on the back: a modern, edgy, industrial-style structure that contrasts sharply with the heritage bluestone frontage. It sounds romantic, but the reality is far from that. Storm water damage means the whole front wall has to be deconstructed and rebuilt, and there's more grief when the original roof won't match up with its new counterpart. Jason and Jen are hands-on when it comes to selecting materials, they have a wedding planned mid-build, and with no architect and tight finances, Jen takes on designing the kitchen and bathroom, as well as starting a new job. The couple are spreading themselves thin in an effort to see their project through. Can they find the balance between the old and the new to salvage this little piece of history?

programme.title: Grand Designs Australia
programme.desc: Peter Maddison presents season five of the Australian architecture show that follows intrepid individuals as they design and construct the home of their dreams. Milly Bradshaw lived with her two children in the Brisbane valley of Brookfield for six years before she met Andrew Wilson. In time, the place became the base for their blended family and was perfect for their shared dream of running a small farm. They started buying cattle, but with their run-down weatherboard cottage well past its use-by date, it was clear they needed a new dwelling: a modern farmhouse. The brief to their architect was simple: a unique home making the best of its location, and as different as possible from the traditional ranch style. Their architect delivered a design that's telescopic, angular and modern in shape, rising from one storey to three and culminating in a two-storey glazed portal framing the master bedroom. Projecting out of the landscape and clad in natural materials such as spotted gum boards, it's a contemporary take on rural living. Andrew, who has plumbing skills, sets out with right-hand man Hamish, an accomplished carpenter, to bring this dynamic form to life. But Milly is busy working so won't be there for the key decisions. The project's scope is breath-taking and even the architect admits it's no easy build. It's supposed to be the next step in their lives together, but as Andrew gets swamped in a quagmire of decision making, it might have the opposite effect
